The assembler debug args are added unconditionally, so release builds
(buildtype=release, debug=false) pay for DWARF generation in nasm.
nasm's DWARF output is very slow on the larger SIMD sources: in a
release build of the decode-only configuration, vp9itxfm.asm alone
takes 55s (vs seconds without -g) and the 76 asm files sum to ~300s of
CPU, with vp9itxfm.asm the last target of the whole build.

Gate the debug format on get_option('debug'), matching how the C side
already behaves, and stop passing bare `-g` to nasm when no debug info
is wanted (on ELF, bare -g still emits DWARF).

---
 meson.build | 8 ++++++--
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/meson.build b/meson.build
--- a/meson.build
+++ b/meson.build
@@ -2749,7 +2749,11 @@
 # The only modern debugging format supported by either is DWARF
 #
 # nasm and yasm don't support DWARF in the PE format (Windows)
-if asm_format.startswith('win')
+if not get_option('debug')
+  # No debug info requested; DWARF generation in nasm is also very slow on
+  # the larger SIMD files (tens of seconds per file).
+  debug_format = 'null'
+elif asm_format.startswith('win')
   if cc.get_define('_MSC_FULL_VER') != ''
     debug_format = 'cv8'
   else
@@ -2775,7 +2779,7 @@
 elif x86asm_type == 'nasm'
   if debug_format == 'dwarf'
     asm_args += ['-g', '-F', 'dwarf']
-  else
+  elif debug_format != 'null'
     asm_args += ['-g']
   endif
 endif
